{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Lecstor's Blog","author":"Jason Galea"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"905d4744-8e43-54b2-8858-b652c50be1c9","excerpt":"Continuous deployment with rollback capability, good test coverage, no sprints, small tasks, cross-functional people and teams, fastâ€¦","html":"<p>Continuous deployment with rollback capability, good test coverage, no sprints, small tasks, cross-functional people and teams, fast iteration.</p>\n<h2 id=\"continuous-deployment\"><a href=\"#continuous-deployment\" aria-label=\"continuous deployment permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Continuous deployment</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>deploy every merge to master</li>\n<li>extensive (90%) automated test coverage</li>\n<li>optimised test run time</li>\n<li>Buildkite &#x26; Kubernetes</li>\n<li>no downtime during deployments</li>\n<li>rapid rollback mechanism</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"no-sprints\"><a href=\"#no-sprints\" aria-label=\"no sprints permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>No Sprints</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>2/3 week sprints are mini waterfall</li>\n<li>sacrifice external stakeholders predictability for increased flexibility</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"small-tasks\"><a href=\"#small-tasks\" aria-label=\"small tasks permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Small Tasks</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>splitting up tasks into <em>small, incremental pieces</em> and shipping each of them separately is the fastest way to deliver value</li>\n<li>reduces deployment risks</li>\n<li>maximises release rate</li>\n<li>feature flagging is a last option, used sparingly</li>\n<li>no feature branches</li>\n<li>small, short-lived PRs</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"cross-functional-people-and-teams\"><a href=\"#cross-functional-people-and-teams\" aria-label=\"cross functional people and teams permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Cross-functional people and teams</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>If you want to optimize for a tight feedback loop, <em>cross-functional teams</em> make a lot more sense than teams <em>split up by skills</em>.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"iterate-or-die\"><a href=\"#iterate-or-die\" aria-label=\"iterate or die permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Iterate or die</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>optimizing for <em>fast iteration speed</em> is not the same thing as <em>throughput</em></li>\n<li>learning from feedback continuously is key</li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":"Optimizing for iteration speed","date":"April 23, 2019","origDate":"July 06, 2017","author":"Erik Bernhardsson","type":"notes","url":"https://erikbern.com/2017/07/06/optimizing-for-iteration-speed.html"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/notes-optimizing-for-iteration-speed/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/optimise-with-react-memo/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Optimising with React.memo"}},"next":null}}